and, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1440–1466":"circa 1440–1466","1440–1466":"1440–1466","1442–1522":"1442–1522","1443–1489":"1443–1489","1452–1520":"1452–1520","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1420–1489":"1420–1489","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1489":"1489","1522":"1522","1466":"1466","1520":"1520","1443":"1443","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","Abt 1440":"circa 1440","1452":"1452","1418":"1418","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Rothbury, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1440–1466":"about 1440–1466","1440–1466":"1440–1466","1442–1522":"1442–1522","1443–1489":"1443–1489","1452–1520":"1452–1520","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1420–1489":"1420–1489","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1489":"1489","1522":"1522","1466":"1466","1520":"1520","1443":"1443","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","Abt 1440":"about 1440","1452":"1452","1418":"1418","England":"England, United Kingdom","Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rowland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Rollant</i>, <i>Rolant</i>, <i>Rolent</i>, <i>Roulent</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Hrodland</i>, <i>Rodland</i>, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘glory’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’), introduced into England by the Normans. It was made famous by French romances about <i>Roland</i>, the most famous of the peers of Charlemagne who was killed at Roncesvalles in  AD  778. Although widely used across post-Conquest England (along with <i>Oliver</i>, the name of Roland's companion), it seems to have been restricted to particular gentry families and was never popular. Compare   Roland  .","English: habitational name from Rowland (Derbyshire) or Rowland Wood in Slinfold (Sussex). The Derbyshire placename derives from Old Norse <i>rá</i> ‘roe, roe buck’ or <i>rá</i> ‘land mark, boundary’ + <i>lúndr</i> ‘small wood, grove’. The Sussex placename probably derives from Middle English <i>roughe</i> ‘rough’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>rūh</i>, <i>land</i>).","English: in northern England and perhaps elsewhere, perhaps a post-medieval variant of   Rawling  . Compare   Rawlinson  ,   Rollinson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Roland","meanings":["French, Walloon, German, English, and Scottish: from an ancient Germanic personal name composed of <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the more common French variant   Rolland  . See also English   Rowland  .","Norwegian (also <b>Røland</b>): habitational name from any of several farms named Rødland mainly in Hordaland or Røyland mainly in Agder, most of them from Old Norse <i>reyrr</i> ‘heap of stones’ or <i>reyrr</i> ‘rush’ (a plant) + the second element <i>land</i> ‘(piece of) land, farmstead’. Compare   Rolland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Roland in Lillehammer, with the first element Old Norse <i>ruth</i> ‘clearing’, or Roland in Agder around Lindesnes, with the first element possibly the Old Norse personal name <i>Rói</i> (either a short form of names beginning with <i>Ro(d)-</i> ‘fame, honor’ or composed with a word for ‘giant’ or ‘pagan priest’). The second element of the farm names is <i>land</i> ‘(piece of) land, farmstead’."]},{"name":"Rollison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal names <i>Rouland</i> or <i>Roulin</i>; see   Rowland  ,   Rolling  . Alternatively, and perhaps more likely, the name may be a post-medieval pronunciation of   Rawlinson  ."]},{"name":"Orlando","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Rocco, Sal, Vito, Antonio, Carlo, Marco, Santo, Carmine, Giovanni, Cosimo.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Orlando</i>, earlier <i>Rolando</i> (see   Rowland  )."]},{"name":"Reuland","meanings":["German: from a personal name, the German form of <i>Roland</i> (see   Rowland  )."]},{"name":"Rolling","meanings":["English: variant of   Rowland  , with <i>-ling</i> substituted for <i>-land</i>.","English: habitational name from Rowling Court in Goodnestone (Kent) or Rowling Street in Bilsington (Kent). The origins of these placenames are uncertain, but they may both derive from an unattested Old English word related to an ancient Germanic base <i>rull-</i> ‘something round’ + the Old English placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>.","English: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Ro(u)lin</i>, a diminutive of either <i>Roll</i> (<i>Rolf</i>) or <i>Rol(l)and</i>. See   Rolfe   and   Rowland  ."]},{"name":"Rowlands","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Rowland  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Rowlett","meanings":["English: from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Rol(l)and</i>. See   Rowland   and compare   Rolling  .","English: from a pet form of the personal name   Ralph  . Compare   Rawling  .","English: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Rolf</i>. See   Rolfe   and compare   Rolling  ."]},{"name":"Rowlan","meanings":["English (South London): variant of   Rowland   with loss of <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Rouland","meanings":["English: variant of   Rowland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Rauland  .","In some cases possibly also French: variant of   Roland  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Rowland I was born about 1440, in Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Rowland, was 23 and his mother,